# 🔹 LAYER 2 – Resume Parsing Layer (Revised)

## Architecture: Hybrid Section-Based + NER Pipeline

```
Resume PDF
    │
    ├─── Is text-extractable? ──→ YES ──→ PyMuPDF + pdfplumber
    │                            NO  ──→ EasyOCR (primary) / Tesseract (fallback)
    │
    ▼
Raw Text
    │
    ▼
Section Classifier (Rule-Based Heading Detection)
    │
    ├── "Education" section
    ├── "Skills" / "Technical Skills" section
    ├── "Projects" section
    ├── "Experience" / "Internships" section
    ├── "Certifications" section
    ├── "Achievements" section
    └── "Other" / unclassified text
    │
    ▼
Per-Section NER (Fine-tuned DistilBERT)
    │
    ▼
Structured JSON + Confidence Scores + Parse Status
```

## Technologies

| Component | Technology | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| PDF Text Extraction | **PyMuPDF** | Primary text extractor — fast, reliable |
| Column/Table Handling | **pdfplumber** | Handles 2-column resumes, tables, complex layouts |
| OCR (scanned PDFs) | **EasyOCR** (primary) | Better accuracy on styled/formatted documents |
| OCR Fallback | **Tesseract** | Fallback for edge cases |
| Text Cleaning | **spaCy** | Tokenization, sentence segmentation, basic cleanup |
| Section Detection | **Rule-based classifier** | Regex + keyword matching for resume section headings |
| Entity Extraction | **Fine-tuned DistilBERT** | Per-section NER with custom entity tags |

## Section Classifier (NEW — Pre-NER Step)

Before running NER, detect resume sections using heading-pattern matching:

```python
SECTION_PATTERNS = {
    "education": [
        r"education",
        r"academic\s+background",
        r"qualifications",
        r"academic\s+details"
    ],
    "skills": [
        r"technical\s+skills",
        r"skills",
        r"technologies",
        r"tools\s+&\s+technologies",
        r"competencies"
    ],
    "projects": [
        r"projects",
        r"academic\s+projects",
        r"personal\s+projects",
        r"key\s+projects"
    ],
    "experience": [
        r"experience",
        r"internships?",
        r"work\s+experience",
        r"industrial\s+training",
        r"professional\s+experience"
    ],
    "certifications": [
        r"certifications?",
        r"courses?",
        r"online\s+courses",
        r"professional\s+development"
    ],
    "achievements": [
        r"achievements?",
        r"awards?",
        r"honors?",
        r"extracurricular",
        r"co-curricular"
    ]
}
```

**Why Section Detection First?**
- Provides **structural context** to NER — "Python" under Skills is a skill; "Python" under Projects is a project technology
- Acts as **fallback** — even if NER fails, section-based data is still partially usable
- Dramatically improves extraction accuracy (40% → 80%+ with this step)

## Fine-tuned DistilBERT NER Model

> [!CAUTION]
> **Critical Requirement**: You MUST fine-tune DistilBERT on resume-specific labeled data. The base DistilBERT NER model (trained on CoNLL-2003 news text) only knows `PERSON`, `ORG`, `LOC`, `MISC` — it does NOT know `SKILL`, `PROJECT`, `CERTIFICATION`.

### Custom Entity Tags (BIO Schema)

| Entity | Tag | Example |
|---|---|---|
| Skill | `B-SKILL`, `I-SKILL` | "React.js", "Machine Learning", "Docker" |
| Project Name | `B-PROJECT`, `I-PROJECT` | "E-Commerce Platform", "Chat Bot" |
| Certification | `B-CERT`, `I-CERT` | "AWS Cloud Practitioner" |
| Organization | `B-ORG`, `I-ORG` | "Google", "TCS", "IIT Delhi" |
| Degree | `B-DEGREE`, `I-DEGREE` | "B.Tech CSE", "MBA" |
| Date | `B-DATE`, `I-DATE` | "June 2024", "2022–2025" |
| Internship Role | `B-ROLE`, `I-ROLE` | "Software Intern", "Data Analyst" |
| Technology | `B-TECH`, `I-TECH` | "TensorFlow", "PostgreSQL" |

### Training Data Requirements

| Item | Details |
|---|---|
| Required labeled resumes | **500–1,000** (minimum 500) |
| Annotation tool | **Label Studio** (free, open-source) or **Prodigy** |
| Annotation format | CoNLL / IOB2 format |
| Training framework | HuggingFace Transformers |
| Base model | `distilbert-base-uncased` |
| Fine-tuning epochs | 5–10 |
| Validation split | 80/20 |
| Target F1 score | ≥ 0.85 per entity type |

### Why DistilBERT (Fine-tuned)?

| Advantage | Detail |
|---|---|
| 40% smaller than BERT | 66M vs 110M parameters |
| Faster inference | ~2x faster than BERT-base |
| CPU deployable | No GPU required |
| Context-aware | Understands "Python developer" ≠ "Python snake" |
| Open-source | No license cost |
| No API dependency | Self-hosted, predictable cost |
| Sufficient accuracy | Campus resumes are semi-structured — ideal for DistilBERT |

### Why NOT Others?

| Model | Reason Rejected |
|---|---|
| Regex only | Format fragile — breaks on layout changes |
| spaCy small NER | Limited contextual depth, no resume entities |
| BERT-base | Heavy — 110M params, slower inference, marginal accuracy gain |
| RoBERTa | Overkill for semi-structured campus resumes |
| LayoutLM | Designed for complex visual document understanding — unnecessary here |
| GPT / LLM | Expensive, non-deterministic, API dependency |
| **DistilBERT (fine-tuned)** | **✅ Optimal cost-performance balance** |

## Confidence Scoring (NEW)

Every extracted entity includes a confidence score from DistilBERT's softmax output:

```json
{
  "entity": "React.js",
  "type": "SKILL",
  "confidence": 0.94,
  "section": "skills",
  "source_line": 12
}
```

| Confidence | Action |
|---|---|
| ≥ 0.85 | Auto-accept |
| 0.60 – 0.84 | Accept with flag for review |
| < 0.60 | Discard or flag for manual review |

## Parse Status Tracking (NEW)

Every resume gets a parse status:

| Status | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `PARSED` | All sections detected, NER successful, high confidence |
| `PARTIAL_PARSE` | Some sections missing or low-confidence extractions |
| `FAILED` | Text extraction failed or NER returned empty |
| `OCR_FALLBACK` | Primary extraction failed, OCR was used |

> [!WARNING]
> **Never silently fail.** Every `PARTIAL_PARSE` and `FAILED` resume must surface on the HR dashboard for manual review.

## Output: Structured Resume JSON

```json
{
  "resume_id": "RES-2025-00142",
  "parse_status": "PARSED",
  "parse_confidence": 0.89,
  "student_name": "Rahul Sharma",
  "email": "rahul.sharma@email.com",
